    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-08-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-08-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="246"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d246">
                <head>246. Letter From Secretary of Commerce <persName corresp="#p_HLH1" type="from"
                        >Hodges</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1" type="to"
                        >Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d246fn1">Source: Washington National Records
                        Center, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 40, Secretary of Commerce Files:
                            <gloss target="#t_FRC1">FRC</gloss> 69 A 6828, White House, July–August.
                        No classification marking. Drafted by Behrman and <persName
                            corresp="#p_WTG1">Wyman</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-08-10">August 10, 1964</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Dear Mr. President:</p>
                <p>Following your instructions to seek additional funds for the commercial
                    specialist program of the Foreign Service, Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                        >Rusk</persName> and I have personally appealed to the Senate Appropriations
                    Committee for the addition of one million dollars to State’s budget. The fact
                    that State earlier claimed no increase in its personnel makes it desirable that
                    you call Senator McClellan to indicate your approval of this change in State’s
                    budget. Deputy Under Secretary Crockett of State and Tom Wyman of my staff have
                    detailed the request to the Senator this week, justifying the specific needs and
                    the posts to which the new officers would be assigned.</p>
                <p>For your use, the $1 million would permit assigning 37 new U.S. officers overseas
                    in addition to the existing 149; 15 of the 37 officers would be assigned to
                    posts where there are no commercial officers; we would also add 100 local and 8
                    U.S. clerical assistants. As you know, without these new officers our successful
                    export drive simply cannot be sustained.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HLH1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Luther H. Hodges</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d246fn2">Printed from a copy that indicates <persName
                                corresp="#p_HLH1">Hodges</persName> signed the original.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>P.S. The Senate Subcommittee mark-up of the State Department appeal will
                        start today.<note n="3" xml:id="d246fn3">On an August 6 transmittal
                            memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_WTG1">Wyman</persName> to
                                <persName corresp="#p_HLH1">Hodges</persName>, attached to the
                            source text, <persName corresp="#p_HLH1">Hodges</persName> wrote out the
                            postscript, which in slightly amended form became the typed postscript
                            to this letter.</note>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
